{"title_page": "Charles Edward Pogue", "text_new": "{{For|other people called Pogue|Pogue (surname)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Charles Edward Pogue\n|birth_name = Charles Edward Pogue Jr.\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|01|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n|alias = Chuck Pogue, Charles Pogue         \n|education = [[Highlands High School (Fort Thomas, Kentucky)|Highlands High School]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of Kentucky]]\n|occupation = Screenwriter, playwright, actor\n|years_active = 1983\u2013present\n|notable_works = ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'', ''[[Psycho III]]'', ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'', ''[[D.O.A. (1988 film)|D.O.A.]]'', ''[[Dragonheart]]''\n|spouse = Julieanne Beasley (1987\u2013present)\n|website = {{URL|http://poguespages.blogspot.ca/}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Edward Pogue Jr.''' (born January 18, 1950) is an American [[screenwriter]], [[playwright]] and [[Actor|stage actor]]. He is best known for writing the screenplays of ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'' (1983), ''[[Psycho III]]'' (1986), ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'' (1986) and ''[[Dragonheart]]'' (1996).<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Charles Pogue Filmography|archivedate=March 7, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307233227/https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/531206/Charles-Pogue/filmography|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/531206/Charles-Pogue/filmography}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPogue was born on January 18, 1950 in [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]], the son of Charles Edward Pogue Sr. (1921\u20131994) and Ruth Elizabeth Hick (1921\u20132010). He grew up in [[Fort Thomas, Kentucky]] and graduated from [[Highlands High School (Fort Thomas, Kentucky)|Highlands High School]] in 1968. He earned a degree in theater arts from the [[University of Kentucky]] in 1972 where he was active in theatre productions.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Google Books]]|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Zc0eBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA719&lpg=PA719&dq=charles+edward+pogue:+julieanne+beasley&source=bl&ots=rFCc01tagF&sig=lxttiIL6ZqAmKsEnn8AKQ-FQJpI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjivtHbhOfLAhXI74MKHXPZD6EQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=charles%20edward%20pogue%3A%20julieanne%20beasley&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Northern Kentucky}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPogue began writing plays and screenplays after moving to [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]. He has worked in the science fiction, fantasy, horror, and thriller genres, and he has also scripted several [[Sherlock Holmes]] adaptations: ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'',<ref name=NYT/> ''[[The Sign of Four (1983 film)|The Sign of Four]]'',<ref name=NYT/> and ''[[Hands of a Murderer]]''.<ref name=NYT/>  His most well-known work to date is probably the acclaimed [[The Fly (1986 film)|1986 remake]]<ref name=NYT/> of ''[[The Fly (1958 film)|The Fly]]''; he provided the initial drafts, though his work was heavily rewritten by [[David Cronenberg]], the film's director.<ref>[http://www.scriptwritersnetwork.com/previous/previous_01_2001.asp Charles Edward Pogue - Crusader for Creative Rights] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117084112/http://www.scriptwritersnetwork.com/previous/previous_01_2001.asp |date=November 17, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nHe has expressed his disappointment with the films that were made from his screenplays for ''[[Dragonheart]]''<ref name=NYT/> and ''[[Kull the Conqueror]]'',<ref name=NYT/> saying that they were ruined by studio interference.<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web |last1=Linder |first1=Brian |title=10 Questions: Charles Edward Pogue |url=https://m.ign.com/articles/2002/05/15/10-questions-charles-edward-pogue |website=IGN |date=15 May 2002}}</ref> Whereas he believes that his most satisfying achievement was ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]''.<ref name=\"ign\"/>\n\nPogue is also a renowned actor in [[Regional theater in the United States|regional theater]] who has worked onstage with such stars as [[Charlton Heston]], [[Jeremy Brett]], [[Cyd Charisse]], [[Martha Raye]] and [[Deanna Dunagan]].\n\nFrom 1997 to 2001, Pogue served on the Board of Directors of the [[Writers Guild of America, West]].\n\nPogue and his wife Julieanne Beasley reside in [[Georgetown, Kentucky]]. They are both very active in theatre productions and he frequently works with the Actors Guild of Lexington in [[Lexington, Kentucky]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Director !! Notes\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'' || [[Douglas Hickox]] || TV movie\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[The Sign of Four (1983 film)|The Sign of Four]]'' || [[Desmond Davis]] || TV movie\n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Psycho III]]'' || [[Anthony Perkins]] ||\n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'' || [[David Cronenberg]] ||\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[D.O.A. (1988 film)|D.O.A.]]'' || [[Rocky Morton]] and [[Annabel Jankel]] ||\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Hands of a Murderer]]'' || Stuart Orme || TV movie\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Dragonheart]]'' || [[Rob Cohen]] ||\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Kull the Conqueror]]'' || [[John Nicolella]] ||\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hercules (miniseries)|Hercules]]'' || [[Roger Young (director)|Roger Young]] || TV miniseries\n|}\n\n==Plays==\n*''Whoddunit, Darling?'' (1983)\n*''The Ebony Ape'' (1987)\n*''[[Tartuffe]]'' (2007)\n\n==Novels==\n*''[[Dragonheart#Novelization|Dragonheart]]'' (1996; based on his original screenplay)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0688279}}\n* [http://poguespages.blogspot.com/ Pogue's Pages]\n* [http://www.wordplayer.com/pros/pr06.Pogue.Charles.Edward.html Writing from the Soul] by Charles Edward Pogue\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pogue, Charles Edward}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Thomas, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:People from Georgetown, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Highlands High School (Fort Thomas, Kentucky) alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Kentucky alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people called Pogue|Pogue (surname)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Charles Edward Pogue\n|birth_name = Charles Edward Pogue Jr.\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|01|18}}\n|birth_place = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n|alias = Chuck Pogue, Charles Pogue         \n|education = [[Highlands High School (Fort Thomas, Kentucky)|Highlands High School]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of Kentucky]]\n|occupation = Screenwriter, playwright, actor\n|years_active = 1983\u2013present\n|notable_works = ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'', ''[[Psycho III]]'', ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'', ''[[D.O.A. (1988 film)|D.O.A.]]'', ''[[Dragonheart]]''\n|spouse = Julieanne Beasley (1987\u2013present)\n|website = {{URL|http://poguespages.blogspot.ca/}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Edward Pogue Jr.''' (born January 18, 1950) is an American [[screenwriter]], [[playwright]] and [[Actor|stage actor]]. He is best known for writing the screenplays of ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'' (1983), ''[[Psycho III]]'' (1986), ''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'' (1986) and ''[[Dragonheart]]'' (1996).<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Charles Pogue Filmography|archivedate=March 7, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307233227/https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/531206/Charles-Pogue/filmography|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/531206/Charles-Pogue/filmography}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPogue was born on January 18, 1950 in [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]], the son of Charles Edward Pogue Sr. (1921\u20131994) and Ruth Elizabeth Hick (1921\u20132010). He grew up in [[Fort Thomas, Kentucky]] and graduated from [[Highlands High School (Fort Thomas, Kentucky)|Highlands High School]] in 1968. He earned a degree in theater arts from the [[University of Kentucky]] in 1972 where he was active in theatre productions.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Google Books]]|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Zc0eBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA719&lpg=PA719&dq=charles+edward+pogue:+julieanne+beasley&source=bl&ots=rFCc01tagF&sig=lxttiIL6ZqAmKsEnn8AKQ-FQJpI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjivtHbhOfLAhXI74MKHXPZD6EQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=charles%20edward%20pogue%3A%20julieanne%20beasley&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Northern Kentucky}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPogue began writing plays and screenplays after moving to [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]. He has worked in the science fiction, fantasy, horror, and thriller genres, and he has also scripted several [[Sherlock Holmes]] adaptations: ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'',<ref name=NYT/> ''[[The Sign of Four (1983 film)|The Sign of Four]]'',<ref name=NYT/> and ''[[Hands of a Murderer]]''.<ref name=NYT/>  His most well-known work to date is probably the acclaimed [[The Fly (1986 film)|1986 remake]]<ref name=NYT/> of ''[[The Fly (1958 film)|The Fly]]''; he provided the initial drafts, though his work was heavily rewritten by [[David Cronenberg]], the film's director.<ref>[http://www.scriptwritersnetwork.com/previous/previous_01_2001.asp Charles Edward Pogue - Crusader for Creative Rights] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117084112/http://www.scriptwritersnetwork.com/previous/previous_01_2001.asp |date=November 17, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nHe has expressed his disappointment with the films that were made from his screenplays for ''[[Dragonheart]]''<ref name=NYT/> and ''[[Kull the Conqueror]]'',<ref name=NYT/> saying that they were ruined by studio interference.<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web |last1=Linder |first1=Brian |title=10 Questions: Charles Edward Pogue |url=https://m.ign.com/articles/2002/05/15/10-questions-charles-edward-pogue |website=IGN |date=15 May 2002}}</ref> Whereas he believes that his most satisfying achievement was ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]''.<ref name=\"ign\"/>\n\nPogue is also a renowned actor in [[Regional theater in the United States|regional theater]] who has worked onstage with such stars as [[Charlton Heston]], [[Jeremy Brett]], [[Cyd Charisse]], [[Martha Raye]] and [[Deanna Dunagan]].\n\nFrom 1997 to 2001, Pogue served on the Board of Directors of the [[Writers Guild of America, West]].\n\nPogue and his wife Julieanne Beasley reside in [[Georgetown, Kentucky]]. They are both very active in theatre productions and he frequently works with the Actors Guild of Lexington in [[Lexington, Kentucky]].\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1983 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'' (1983) (TV movie)\n*''[[The Sign of Four (1983 film)|The Sign of Four]]'' (1983) (TV movie)\n*''[[Psycho III]]'' (1986)\n*''[[The Fly (1986 film)|The Fly]]'' (1986) (with [[David Cronenberg]])\n*''[[D.O.A. (1988 film)|D.O.A.]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Hands of a Murderer]]'' (1990) (TV movie)\n*''[[Dragonheart]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Kull the Conqueror]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Hercules (miniseries)|Hercules]]'' (2001) (TV miniseries)\n\n==Plays==\n*''Whoddunit, Darling?'' (1983)\n*''The Ebony Ape'' (1987)\n*''[[Tartuffe]]'' (2007)\n\n==Novels==\n*''[[Dragonheart#Novelization|Dragonheart]]'' (1996; based on his original screenplay)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0688279}}\n* [http://poguespages.blogspot.com/ Pogue's Pages]\n* [http://www.wordplayer.com/pros/pr06.Pogue.Charles.Edward.html Writing from the Soul] by Charles Edward Pogue\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pogue, Charles Edward}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Thomas, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:People from Georgetown, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Highlands High School (Fort Thomas, Kentucky) alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Kentucky alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Kentucky]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Edward_Pogue"}
{"title_page": "Leraldo Anzaldua", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Leraldo Anzaldua\n| image         =\n| image_size    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1975|06|22}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Houston]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~thtr/people/bio/lAnzaldua.shtml|title=Leraldo Anzaldua {{!}} Department of Theatre, Drama, and Contemporary Dance|website=www.indiana.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n| occupation    = Voice actor, actor, stunt coordinator, ADR director, script writer \n}}\n'''Leraldo Anzaldua''' (born June 22, 1975 in [[Houston]], [[Texas]], USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1453891/|title=Leraldo Anzaldua|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>) is an American voice actor, ADR director, scriptwriter and stunt coordinator who works with [[A.D. Vision|ADV Films]] and [[Seraphim Digital]]/[[Sentai Filmworks]]. He has an [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A]]. in acting from the University of Houston. In anime, he is known for providing the English voice of Yuta Togashi from the ''[[Chunibyo]]'' series, Ken Washio in ''[[Science Ninja Team Gatchaman|Gatchaman]]'', Takashi Komuro in ''[[Highschool of the Dead]]'', and Zed in ''[[Kiba (anime)|Kiba]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Anime===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Source\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Kids on the Slope]]''\n|Additional Voices\n|\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Btooom!|Btooom]]''\n|Tsuneaki Ida\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-11-08/sentai-filmworks-unveils-btooom-s-dub-cast|title=Sentai Filmworks Unveils Btooom!'s Dub Cast|work=Anime News Network|access-date=2017-06-17|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Chaika - The Coffin Princess]]'' series\n|Toru Acura\n|also season 2\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-11-03/chaika-the-coffin